Multiple epiphyseal dysplasia is a skeletal disorder characterized by short stature and early-onset osteoarthrosis (Briggs et al., 1995).

Genetic Heterogeneity of Multiple Epiphyseal Dysplasia

Multiple epiphyseal dysplasia is a genetically heterogeneous disorder. See also EDM2, caused by mutation in the COL9A2 gene; EDM3, caused by mutation in the COL9A3 gene; EDM4, caused by mutation in the DTDST gene; EDM5, caused by mutation in the MATN3 gene; and EDM6, caused by mutation in the COL9A1 gene.

[Briggs, M. D., Hoffman, S. M. G., King, L. M., Olsen, A. S., Mohrenweiser, H., Leroy, J. G., Mortier, G. R., Rimoin, D. L., Lachman, R. S., Gaines, E. S., Cekleniak, J. A., Knowlton, R. G., Cohn, D. H. Pseudoachondroplasia and multiple epiphyseal dysplasia due to mutations in the cartilage oligomeric matrix protein gene. Nature Genet. 10: 330-336, 1995.]<br/>